TextBlock.TextLine: C 29 Julij 1682
londen Joregn Sabbarton
you save answered mine of the 18th past to m flay, yd of the ½d, I
have reed m. Clay hath recd of m. mullan £100- flemish, with promise
to pay £150- more yeasterday, butt de is suddainly you for Brussels, though
this day exspected sere againe, so wee will not loose any time to gett itt
or force dim to itt, the 2 packetts N.1 & H shall be sent o newport nept
fuiday to m. de vallegs to follow yd order, In case you have not alread
been with nr. warner, I would advise yon not to go, because mee thinghes
I shall continew in dis commissios, remember mee toall freinds &
londen seon loyd
In answer toyd of tth caritt. as for the bale of tykes is past to yd acctt for I
never sended any for my owne, & shough you complaine, yett I hope you will
finde yd acctt. att last, & Jf you should not, I'll rather allow some a bater
on the ¼ 3 seales, you please to observe that the com is much restr hem
againe, so that itt is a Gaid matter to have any thingh cheaper, & I do
not know bow any other could sill, better then you, othero allowing mee
more & provision, & now you see did not yett trouble you for the valew, &
Il I draw att tux, you will I lope have sold them alls & rad the valee for
to pay itt there with as for laces, I serve severale frrinds in london & sulm
so thar I may not be concerned, other wise I would, & for a tryall I'll send yu
a small parcell, on which you may depend, as also on my endeavour to
observe yd. Intrest in all as for my owne
C 29d.
Epon Will Hobbe & Coms
yd of the first curtt. I did not answer, because I thought itt was yd
ernor, at by yd of 5d. I finde. I have made you debtor for an errer
In the bale n. 2:3 where you clarge mee for £12:8:6 which is butt
£12:1- N 7ƒ:6 pence to my preiudice, I lave reed yd. invoyce
& pat. of 3 bales aboard Ewings, for which shall given yu credt
you dave not shipt them in the fiust vessel, seeng that wills is rady
& no news of lwings, buy no more serges sill forther order, & lest me
dave the perpet, which you dave already bought, & rather then to
allow more, would have you send onely what you have ready, for wee must
buy good cheap, & good goods, or elce wee can do no good upon them den
so pray do yd ut most formee, & space mee wiil yd drausts as long as pon you u
without yds preud, m Cole will accept yd bills
a 29d.
London Geonge Cole
mij last to you was on the 22t suitt unts which I do exspect you answer, then also
desixed you would be pleased so accept some thing for mee of m. W. Lobbs dut
the whole will be about £200- butt not above which I hope be shall draw onyd
att some tme, when due draw on mee att 2 vke & yd. bill shall be duely difeey
In opspeckn bp yd answer
London Luey Kingltley
haveing been ont of touwne did not sooner artswer yd of 3 & 10 cut ar for
the bill of £100- I do not quession butt what you did, was by the desire of
m. Collier of is sonne, in the meane while I hope you will not blame mee
for accepting the same got yd. donour & acctt, as I should do, where soever I
should mist with the like of yd sand in what ou soever, except I gad
yd contra order, m. Collier hath promised mee to rembourse mee which I
do not doubt butt be will ferforme, for I everfound dim as good as inword
& I gould be vere sorry that this should be, or cause the least breack in yd
frend schip to dim. I shall exannu yd. acctt, & remitt you the ballance
p frust, for though you pretend to bave oa for mony, yett I can sardel, beleave
itt, yett that shall make no way, for mee to keep you from yd. butt with
thanck fullnes endeavour to satisfee you a
London Enry Collier
mij last toyou wat in the 2ith curtt. sence recd yd of 10 d. I have wrett us.
imgetley this day, which I hope will give un contf. I do not expect see
will servple you in the least, or blame for what you save don, for you are
more intimated then to be sefarated for so small a cause, if you please to
have mee pay yd bill with donour remitt mee the valee for I do not know
how to pay itt & reddaw itt to some body elee butt sun, seeng I must need
remitt dom, so shall exspect yd. remise
Lave a leser J Wanne
by which mee thincker, ie es better resolved then when se was sere
the widdon boelo is blawne up & n avay, & cheated many, & mee inte
the rest, itt is se bad asome here, that wee have much a do to considder
how to beuss any boddy. I seave cmore bad debts, god preserve mee for
all om wale fare depends under the peoplen Bickley is come over
there & new war touse againe
london Henry Willinghton
C 29d.
volgens 22 deser aen ul hadde ges hadde gemeijns de cansen ul
gesonden te hebben, dogh icq hende geen pant de venise naer mijn
sin, pours de lorene oft de france die comt van bans, soo dat
Ick niet en ordeele beeter soude wesen als port de malene, dogh alsoo
Ick bevinde ul niet en deest getermineert wat pant seg neemen bionde
soo hebe eerst goet gedaght ul aen m. ab. vivian te adviseeren den
welcken seer schoone pourt de malne heeft & ul aen 't gene noodigh
hebe sal comen dienen, ten miusten sal ul bij hem connen saen oft ul
sulckex sorte gelieft te hebben, den welcke dan op ul ord sal sejnden
ofte de £200- r, terugge ul antw te gemoet siende
